WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.440 --> 00:00:10.440
One of my missions in life is to make getting proficient on the mainframe as simple and painless as possible.

2
00:00:10.440 --> 00:00:19.440
However, there is such a thing as oversimplifying, and I get a little set off when I hear someone explain datasets as,

3
00:00:19.440 --> 00:00:21.440
well, a dataset is just a file.

4
00:00:21.440 --> 00:00:31.440
And it's a dangerous generalization to make because for a few basic examples, yeah, it appears like a dataset is the same thing as a file,

5
00:00:31.440 --> 00:00:33.440
and they have a lot of the same characteristics.

6
00:00:33.440 --> 00:00:41.440
But once you dig just a little bit deeper, you'll see there are some very important differences to know about.

7
00:00:41.440 --> 00:00:46.440
So first off, a dataset can be either sequential or partitioned.

8
00:00:46.440 --> 00:00:55.440
A sequential dataset is full of entries called records, and they go one right after the other, after the other, after the other, like a stack of pancakes.

9
00:00:56.440 --> 00:00:59.440
A partitioned dataset has a directory and members.

10
00:00:59.440 --> 00:01:08.440
The directory keeps track of all the members, so they don't have to be in order, and it also makes it possible for each member to be accessed directly.

11
00:01:08.440 --> 00:01:14.440
This is what kind of closely resembles the files in a folder structure you're probably familiar with.

12
00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:17.440
So what do we use these datasets for?

13
00:01:17.440 --> 00:01:20.440
Use datasets for storing data.

14
00:01:20.440 --> 00:01:28.440
If you're dealing with data that comes out of a program, it typically comes out line by line, and each line is recorded as a record.

15
00:01:28.440 --> 00:01:34.440
In a sequential dataset, you've just got record after record, output after output.

16
00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:39.440
And it could be a series of passenger numbers or a listing of company names.

17
00:01:39.440 --> 00:01:46.440
In a partitioned dataset, that same data gets stored as records within the PDS members.

18
00:01:47.440 --> 00:01:52.440
And if you're writing or reading a text file, each line in that is a record.

19
00:01:52.440 --> 00:02:02.440
So in a sequential dataset, records go into a dataset, and in a partitioned dataset, records go into members, which go into a dataset.

20
00:02:02.440 --> 00:02:08.440
There are two kinds of partitioned datasets, PDSs and PDSEs.

21
00:02:08.440 --> 00:02:19.440
PDSEs are an enhancement to the original PDS design, and have greater flexibility in sizing, faster searching, and automatically reclaim space when members are deleted.

22
00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:25.440
There's only a few places in ZOS where you're required to use a PDS instead of a PDSE.

23
00:02:25.440 --> 00:02:28.440
Everywhere else, people just use a PDSE.

24
00:02:28.440 --> 00:02:33.440
There's also a very powerful type of dataset called a VSAM dataset.

25
00:02:33.440 --> 00:02:36.440
That stands for Virtual Storage Access Method.

26
00:02:36.440 --> 00:02:42.440
And that's another acronym I had to look up just to tell you what it stands for, because everyone just calls it VSAM.

27
00:02:42.440 --> 00:02:44.440
So just call it VSAM.

28
00:02:44.440 --> 00:02:50.440
A VSAM dataset uses a series of keys to reference the actual pieces of data being stored.

29
00:02:50.440 --> 00:03:02.440
It actually quite closely resembles something like a NoSQL database, and it's used primarily by applications directly, since you can't display or edit its contents in something like ISPF.

30
00:03:02.440 --> 00:03:12.440
There's a lot to VSAM, and it has many uses, but because we'll be using ISPF for many of our labs, we'll be focusing on PDS datasets.

31
00:03:12.440 --> 00:03:18.440
A PDS dataset name can be anywhere from one to a series of 22 joined name segments.

32
00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:23.440
So, Jeff.Loves.Pizza is a valid dataset name.

33
00:03:23.440 --> 00:03:25.440
It's also true.

34
00:03:25.440 --> 00:03:32.440
Jeff is the high-level qualifier, Loves is another qualifier, and Pizza is the low-level qualifier.

35
00:03:32.440 --> 00:03:42.440
Obviously, qualifiers are separated by a period, and you can use a maximum of 44 characters in total, including the periods.

36
00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:45.440
So, you've got these qualifiers separated by periods.

37
00:03:45.440 --> 00:03:52.440
Each qualifier must begin with an alphanumeric character, or the special character, at, hash, or dollar sign.

38
00:03:52.440 --> 00:04:02.440
The characters after that can be alphanumeric, special, or numeric, and each qualifier must be one to eight characters in length.

39
00:04:02.440 --> 00:04:16.440
Dollar sign 32.4.Pizza is a valid dataset name, as long as the 4 is spelled out F-O-R and not the number 4, because a dataset qualifier can't start with a number.

40
00:04:16.440 --> 00:04:20.440
$32 for pizza? That's a little ridiculous, right?

41
00:04:20.440 --> 00:04:25.440
Anyway, sys1.ParmLive, well, that better be a valid dataset name.

42
00:04:25.440 --> 00:04:35.440
So, i.sure.do.love.this.awesome.system is a valid dataset name, because it has less than 44 characters total.

43
00:04:35.440 --> 00:04:41.440
You should try to have some order, though, and not use names that might confuse people.

44
00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:45.440
Just because you can do it, sometimes doesn't mean you should.

45
00:04:45.440 --> 00:04:54.440
Now, to use a dataset, it must first be allocated, and allocated just means it exists in a way that we can reference it as an object.

46
00:04:54.440 --> 00:04:56.440
We have a link to it.

47
00:04:56.440 --> 00:05:04.440
So, before we can type anything into a dataset, we need to allocate it, since the dataset we're typing into is going to take up space.

48
00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:06.440
Makes sense, right?

49
00:05:06.440 --> 00:05:14.440
One of the easiest ways of allocating a dataset is through the ISPF panel, made specifically for datasets.

50
00:05:14.440 --> 00:05:26.440
So, in ISPF, if we go to option 3 for utilities, and then option 2 for dataset, we can use option A for allocate.

51
00:05:26.440 --> 00:05:33.440
And we can take ISPF's suggestions for naming a dataset using these three fields, the project, group, and type.

52
00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:35.440
That's a good start.

53
00:05:35.440 --> 00:05:38.440
Or I can just type out the name of the dataset that I want down here.

54
00:05:38.440 --> 00:05:48.440
It's up to you, but if you want to have more than three qualifiers, you'll have to use the field down here, labeled other partition sequential or VSAM datasets.

55
00:05:48.440 --> 00:05:53.440
On the next screen, you need to decide if you want a sequential or a partition dataset.

56
00:05:53.440 --> 00:06:02.440
The steps are largely the same, except that for a sequential, you specify zero blocks for the directory, because a sequential dataset has no directory.

57
00:06:02.440 --> 00:06:04.440
Everything is just in order.

58
00:06:04.440 --> 00:06:11.440
To create a PDSE, you specify the word library in the dataset name type field over here.

59
00:06:11.440 --> 00:06:16.440
If you did this right, you'll get this message up top saying dataset allocated.

60
00:06:16.440 --> 00:06:21.440
And if you get anything else, just go back and retrace your steps. It's probably something simple.

61
00:06:21.440 --> 00:06:27.440
Either way, now you see why datasets are not the same thing as files.
